description: From French complexe, from Latin complexus, past participle of complector (“I entwine, encircle, compass, infold”), from com- (“together”) and plectere (“to weave, braid”). May be analyzed as com- +‎ -plex. See complect. Doublet of complexus.

adjectives.description: complex (comparative complexer or more complex, superlative complexest or most complex)

entries.meaning: Made up of multiple parts; composite; not simple.
examples: a complex being; a complex idea

entries.meaning: Not simple, easy, or straightforward; complicated.
(mathematics, of a number) Having the form a + bi, where a and b are real numbers and i is (by definition) the imaginary square root of −1.
(mathematics, mathematical analysis, of a function) Whose range is a subset of the complex numbers.
(mathematics, algebra) Whose coefficients are complex numbers; defined over the field of complex numbers.
(geometry) A curve, polygon or other figure that crosses or intersects itself.
A collection of buildings with a common purpose, such as a university or military base.

definitionGroups.group: An assemblage of related things; a collection.

entries.meaning: A cluster of wildfires burning in the same vicinity.
examples: The fire complex began as two separate fires.

entries.meaning: (taxonomy) A group of closely related species, often distinguished only with difficulty by traditional morphological methods.
(psychoanalysis) An abnormal mental condition caused by repressed emotions.
(informal, by extension) A vehement, often excessive psychological dislike or fear of a particular thing.
examples: Jim has a real complex about working for a woman boss.

entries.meaning: (chemistry) A structure consisting of a central atom or molecule weakly connected to surrounding atoms or molecules, as for example coordination complexes in inorganic chemistry and protein complexes in biochemistry.
(linguistics) A multimorphemic word, one with several parts, one with affixes.

verbs.description: complex (third-person singular simple present complexes, present participle complexing, simple past and past participle complexed)

entries.meaning: (chemistry, intransitive) To form a complex with another substance
